  "text": "anchor Image: Shuaizhi Tian/Pexels Construction input prices decreased by 0.2% for the month of December, according to a new Associated Builders and Contractors (ABC) analysis of U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics Producer Price Index data. Nonresidential construction input prices decreased 0.2% for the month, and overall construction input prices are 0.9% higher than a year ago. December’s nonresidential construction input prices are now also 0.6% higher. Prices for steel mill products (-3.0%) and iron and steel (-2.5%) dropped while the price of softwood lumber (1.1%) and hot rolled steel bars, plates, and structural shapes (2.5%) increased. Chart credit: Associated Builders and Contractors“Construction materials prices declined slightly in December and are virtually unchanged over the past two years,” ABC Chief Economist Anirban Basu said. “Of course, there is significant variability across input categories. Much of the recent moderation can be tracked to lower energy prices; diesel prices, for instance, are down roughly $0.45/gallon since December 2023.\" Chart credit: Associated Builders and Contractors\"Prices for other inputs, like copper wire and cable or sand and gravel products, have escalated significantly over the past year. For the industry, however, the fact that overall input prices have remained flat in recent quarters is purely good news. Just 20% of contractors expect their profit margins to decline over the next six months, according to ABC’s Construction Confidence Index,\" his statement continued. Basu's predictions for the year ahead were recently included in our Architecture Community 2025 Predictions feature. The ABC analysis of November's construction input price data can also be found here. Similar articles on Archinect that may interest you... Construction costs projected to see largest increase in years due to supply and demand pressures Construction input prices climb 1.4% in February Nonresidential construction spending rises by nearly 1% in November, driven by boosts in manufacturing and... Leveling construction material costs and supply chain relief may signal inflation cooling, new report finds Construction input prices drop again for December, driven by declines in all sectors Construction input prices rise 1% for January following December drop",
